\paragraph{Supervised Fine-Tuning (SFT).}
We fine-tune both the \texttt{Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.2} and \texttt{Qwen2.5-7B-Instruct} models using Low-Rank Adaptation (LoRA) on the full multilingual training set. For \texttt{Qwen2.5-7B}, we employ a rank $r=8$, $\alpha=32$, and dropout $0.05$, targeting the \texttt{q\_proj}, \texttt{k\_proj}, \texttt{v\_proj}, \texttt{o\_proj}, \texttt{gate\_proj}, \texttt{up\_proj}, and \texttt{down\_proj} layers. For \texttt{Mistral-7B}, we utilize a configuration with $r=16$, $\alpha=32$, and dropout $0.1$, targeting the attention projection layers (\texttt{q\_proj}, \texttt{k\_proj}, \texttt{v\_proj}, \texttt{o\_proj}). Both models are trained using 4-bit NormalFloat (NF4) quantization. Training is conducted for $3$ epochs using the AdamW optimizer with a learning rate of $2 \times 10^{-5}$ and a per-device batch size of $1$. We use gradient accumulation with $8$ steps to achieve an effective batch size of $8$. To optimize memory, we enable gradient checkpointing and use the \texttt{expandable\_segments} configuration for the CUDA memory allocator. At inference, models utilize the same chat templates and clinical prompting constraints as established in the zero-shot experiments.
